## Summary: Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Choice | Reason |
|----------|--------|--------|
| Sync Protocol | OT (server-based) | Proven, lower client complexity |
| Transport | WebSocket | Bidirectional, low latency |
| Hot Storage | Redis | In-memory speed for active docs |
| Cold Storage | PostgreSQL + S3 | Reliability + cost efficiency |
| Scaling | Document sharding | Natural isolation boundary |
| Offline | IndexedDB + Service Worker | Progressive enhancement |
| Conflict Resolution | OT with server authority | Single source of truth |

---

Answer: A real-time collaborative document editing system requires: (1) **OT or CRDT** for conflict resolution — OT with a central server is simpler and proven; (2) **WebSocket connections** for low-latency bidirectional communication; (3) **Collaboration service** that transforms concurrent operations and maintains document revision history; (4) **Tiered storage** — Redis for active documents, PostgreSQL for operation logs, S3 for snapshots/archives; (5) **Presence system** for cursor sharing and awareness; (6) **Document sharding** for horizontal scaling where all users of the same document connect to the same server; (7) **Offline support** via IndexedDB queuing with rebase-on-reconnect; (8) **Periodic snapshots** for efficient version history reconstruction. The core insight is that every edit becomes an operation with a revision number, and the server is the authority that transforms and orders all concurrent operations to ensure convergence. | Confidence: 82%
